       Chapter 2 - Getting Started...
       ﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍ
        a. General Information...
       ﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄ

           NetModem is the Windows  Server  Application. It  shows
           all your nessecary TCP/IP information.  e.g. your  Host 
           Name  on the  Internet, and your IP Address on the net.
           It  also  displays  the  Node  Status, when you have an
           Incoming Connection, and Connection Status. I  may  add
           Caller-ID to this also if enough people want it, but it
           will only be available in the  Registered  version. The
           Server Application should  be the  first thing  loaded,
           not nessecary to  be first  but  a good idea. Right now
           the Application Icon Minimizes to down to the Task  Bar
           but NetModem/32 will Minimize down  to  the  Windows 95
           Icon Tray. (The area near the System Clock).

           NetFOSSIL is the FOSSIL driver for the BBS software  to
           use to communicate via the TCP/IP Telnet Protocol. It's
           the ONLY FOSSIL driver that will work with NetModem. It
           will not work with ADF, X00, nor BNU. Make sure you  do
           not load  another FOSSIL driver  on the  same COMx port
           as the port you told NetFOSSIL to support/emulate. This
           will probably result in lockups and errors of some sort
           . You also MUST load NetFOSSIL in  your AUTOEXEC.BAT so
           it will load before Windows 3.1/95 does If you don't it
           will NOT work so dont  EMail me saying you cant get  it
           to work, when you don't even follow the directions.

       ﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄ

       ﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍ
        b. Installing NetModem...
       ﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄ

           There is only one command parameter for NetModem. It is
           the number of  Nodes/Ports  to support.  The  Shareware
           version only supports 1 Node/Port, so the command  line
           to load NetModem would be:

                              NetModem.EXE 1

           You can use the "Start -> Run" option in Windows 3.1/95
           to start it or create an Icon to execute it. I find the
           Icon easier. Once  started NetModem will  automatically
           Minimize  itself to the  Windows 95 Task Bar.  You  can
           Maximize it  by  clicking  the  Icon. In  the  NetModem
           Window it will display your Host Name. This is the name
           of your machine on the Internet, and in some  cases  it
           can be used as a address for a user to Telnet  into. In
           other cases you must use an IP Address because most ISP
           systems dont assign a Host Name to each individual user
           and this  leaves you  only with your systems IP address
           which no system on  the Internet has  the same. If  you
           choose, in most cases your  ISP may charge a  small fee
           for a custom Host Name off his system.

           e.g.

           If your ISP's Domain Name is:

                       concentric.net

           You may be able to get a Host Name of:

                       yourbbsname.concentric.net

           Or another method is to pay $100 to Internic for a full
           Domain Name this will require a Static IP from your ISP
           and you can get something like this:

           e.g.
                       yourbbsname.com

           Most people tend to stick with IP Addresses or the Host
           Name method but others may prefer thier own Domain Name
           . NetModem is nice because its small, fast, and easy to
           use... NetModem will work  with ANY  doors/program that
           can use a FOSSIL driver.  NetModem also uses 32-Bit CPU
           Instructions...

       ﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄ

       ﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍﾍ
        c. Installing NetFOSSIL...
       ﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄﾄ

           Brief features list of NetFOSSIL...

           ( * = Registered Functions Only )

            - Uses 32-Bit CPU Instructions.
            - It will work with any DOS-based BBS software, or any
              program that can use a FOSSIL Driver.
            - It can run on any Windows 3.1/95 based machine.
            - It can run with any Windows 3.1/95 based TCP/IP
              Network as long as you have WinSock.DLL v1.1 on your
              system.
            - Supports FOSSIL Rev5 Specs.
            - Supports the SuperSet/Extended FOSSIL Functions.
            - 2048k Input and Output Buffer sizes.
            - Emulates Hardware (CTS/RTS) and Software (XOn/XOff)
              Flow Control.
            - No need to work with stupid system IRQ's.
            - It will accept any type connection speed from 300bps
              on up to OC-xxx lines.
            * Supports Multiple Nodes/Inbound Connections.
            * Supports Outbound Connections.
            * Caller-ID Displayed in the NetModem Server App.

           AT Commands that NetFOSSIL will accept...
           
           Although NetFOSSIL  will accept ANY thing  that  begins
           with AT here  are the ones that accually do something..
           Your first init string MUST be ATZH0| if it is not then
           this will go wrong...

            ATA  - Answer a call when "RING" is detected.
            ATZ  - Force an "OK" from the emulated modem/port.
                   (ATZ - also makes BBS go On-Hook/Online.)
            ATH0 - Go On-Hook or make the BBS ready for incoming
                   calls.
            ATH1 - Go Off-Hook or make the BBS not accept incoming
                   calls.

           NetFOSSIL has several command line  paramters that  you
           you must provide for it to function properlly. First of
           all you MUST LOAD NETFOSSL.EXE IN YOUR AUTOEXEC.BAT!!!!
           Command-Line Parameters...

            PORT - Number of comports for NetFOSSIL to emulate. 
             
             ^-- This tells NetFOSSIL the number of COM ports to
                 emulate/support.

            Note: NetFOSSIL it NOT 0 based like X00...
                  3 means Com3, 4 means Com4 etc...

            COMM - Specifies the 1st comport to start emulating.

             ^-- This tells NetFOSSIL the 1st COM port to support/
                 emulate. It will support this COM port and on up.
                 e.g. If you have the 8 Node/Port version and you
                 give it a 6 for COM6 then it will support COM6 &
                 COM... 7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12 & 13 as well. Do  not
                 use a COM port that is in use by a real modem or
                 mouse or such device.
             
            BAUD - Baudrate to lock the comports at.

             ^-- This tells NetFOSSIL what Baudrate to lock all
                 the COM ports that it will be emulating. Valid
                 Baudrates are: 19200, 38400 and 57600.

              Example:

                NETFOSSL.EXE 1 7 38400

                 Tells NetFOSSIL to use NetModem Port 1, emulate
                 COM7 and up, and lock all the ports at 38400bps..
                       
